[[File:Oita nagahama jinja 1.jpg|thumb|right|Torii gate]]
[[File:Oita nagahama jinja 3.jpg|thumb|right|Hina ema (wooden plaques)]]
'''Nagahama Shrine''' (長浜神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located in {{ill|Nagahama Town (Ōita City)|ja|長浜町 (大分市)}}, {{ill|Ōita City|ja|大分市}}, {{ill|Ōita Prefecture|ja|大分県}}. The shrine's primary deity is {{ill|Sukunabikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona}}<ref>[https://www.oita-press.co.jp/1010000000/2015/12/28/132221197 新年の舞「めおと」で 雌の獅子頭奉納 大分市の長浜神社] Ōita Gōdō Shimbun, December 28, 2015</ref>, and it also enshrines {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane}}<ref name="niigata-u">[http://www.niigata-u.com/files/oita/nagahama.html Nagahama Shrine (Nagahama Town, Ōita City)] Ōita Shrine Exploration</ref>. Under the {{ill|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines}}, the shrine was classified as a gōsha.

Nagahama Shrine is particularly revered by women for its association with the healing of gynecological ailments, as it enshrines deities regarded as patrons of medicine, {{ill|Sukunabikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona}} and {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己貴命}}<ref>[http://www.i-oita.net/spot/history_culture/oita/9182.html Nagahama Shrine] iNavi Ōita (Ōita Broadcasting System)</ref>. Devotees traditionally offer wooden plaques (ema) depicting male and female hina dolls when making prayers<ref name="oita012a1">Katsumi Watanabe, "Digital Book Version of 'Ōita Past and Present' Chapter 12: Around Nagahama" {{PDF|[http://www.nan-nan.jp/lib/oita012a1.pdf link]}} Ōita Gōdō Shimbun, November 2, 2007</ref>.

== History ==
According to shrine tradition, Nagahama Shrine was founded in {{ill|Ōei|ja|応永}} 13 (1406). A local resident of Nagahama had a divine dream, and the following morning discovered a small wooden shrine box washed ashore, containing a miniature altar inscribed "Yoshu Nagahama Daimyōjin" on the inner side of its door and a sacred mirror inside. Upon reporting this discovery to {{ill|Ōtomo Chikayo|ja|大友親世}}, the {{ill|Governor of Bungo Province|ja|豊後国守護}}, Chikayo donated shrine land and funds for construction. The shrine was established and named "Nagahama Daimyōjin"<ref name="niigata-u" /><ref>Katsumi Watanabe, "Digital Book Version of 'Ōita Past and Present' Chapter 1: Around Shōwa Avenue" {{PDF|[http://www.nan-nan.jp/lib/oita001a1.pdf link]}} Ōita Gōdō Shimbun, August 17, 2007</ref>.

The shrine was damaged by the tsunami caused by the {{ill|Keichō Bungo earthquake|ja|慶長豊後地震}} on {{ill|July 12 (lunar calendar)|ja|7月12日 (旧暦)}} in {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄}} 5 (1596 CE). It was temporarily relocated to the grounds of {{ill|Kasuga Shrine (Ōita City)|ja|春日神社 (大分市)|1=Kasuga Shrine (Ōita)}} in {{ill|Seie Town (Ōita)|ja|勢家町}} before moving to Shiokyūshō Town in {{ill|Genna|ja|元和}} 5 (1619 CE), and again within the same town to its present location in {{ill|Empō|ja|延宝}} 9 (1681 CE). In {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正}} 2 (1913 CE), the neighboring Matsusue Tenmasha, dedicated to Sugawara no Michizane, was merged into Nagahama Shrine<ref name="niigata-u" /><ref name="oita012a1" />.

== Summer Festival ==
Nagahama Shrine's annual summer festival, held from {{ill|July 5|ja|7月5日}} to {{ill|July 7|ja|7月7日}}, is affectionately called "Nagahama-sama." It traces its origins to the "Nagahama Market," one of Bungo's three great markets, which began during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}. Because the festival often coincides with the rainy season, it is nicknamed "Rainy Nagahama-sama." It is recognized as Ōita's first summer festival of the year, signaling the start of summer<ref name="oita-press_20160621" /><ref name="visit-oita">[http://www.visit-oita.jp/events/detail/8708/ Nagahama Shrine Summer Festival] Ōita Tourism Information Official Website</ref><ref name="oishiimati-oita">[http://www.oishiimati-oita.jp/events/detail/527 Nagahama Shrine Summer Festival] Ōita City Tourism Association</ref><ref name="mainichi">[http://mainichi.jp/articles/20160707/ddl/k44/040/242000c Ōmikoshi Procession Highlighting Nagahama Shrine Festival in Ōita City] Mainichi Shimbun, July 7, 2016</ref><ref name="oitabank">[https://www.oitabank.co.jp/hometown/kawara/kawara-article/150713.html Nagahama Shrine Summer Festival] Yacchoru Dē! Ōita Kawara-ban (Ōita Bank)</ref>.

The festival transforms Shiokyūshō Street and Nagahama Street into pedestrian-only zones, with over 120 stalls and displays of "Fūryū Mitate Saiku" (decorative floats). Highlights include {{ill|Mikoshi|ja|神輿}} processions, {{ill|Kagura|ja|神楽}}, and performances such as Yosakoi and hula dancing on the festival square's opening night<ref name="visit-oita" /><ref name="oishiimati-oita" /><ref name="mainichi" />. The mikoshi procession, dating back to {{ill|Ansei|ja|安政}} 3 (1856 CE) when it was first dedicated by the final feudal lord of the {{ill|Fuchū domain (Bungo)|ja|府内藩}}, {{ill|Matsudaira Chikayoshi|ja|松平近説}}, was halted in 1922 but resumed in {{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和}} 62 (1987 CE)<ref name="oita-press_20160621" />.

During the festival, an auspicious item called "Omika Mochi" is sold. Stems of {{ill|Ligustrum japonicum|ja|ネズミモチ|lt=Privet}} adorned with red, yellow, and green rice cakes and paper strips originated from a legend where a woman named Omika offered such decorations in gratitude for healing. The tradition dates to the {{ill|Empō|ja|延宝}} era and was revived postwar by the local preservation society<ref name="oitabank" />.

== Access ==
* Approximately 15 minutes on foot from {{ill|Ōita Station|ja|大分駅}}, {{ill|JR Kyushu|ja|九州旅客鉄道}}<ref name="oishiimati-oita" />

== References ==
{{Reflist|2}}

